 succeeded in 0ms:
Using profile-level AMCEs estimated with `projoint` and respondent-clustered standard errors, Figure 1 shows clear preferences over several neighborhood attributes. Relative to a housing cost of 15% of pre-tax income, a cost of 40% reduced the probability that a profile was chosen by 19.8 percentage points (pp; 95% CI: -27.4 to -12.2), while a cost of 30% reduced it by 13.7 pp (-20.8 to -6.6). The largest estimated penalty was for a violent-crime rate 20% above the national average rather than 20% below it: -25.1 pp (-33.4 to -16.8). Commuting time also mattered substantially. Compared with 10 minutes of daily driving, 75 minutes lowered profile choice by 23.7 pp (-31.0 to -16.5), and 45 minutes lowered it by 14.1 pp (-21.2 to -6.9). School quality was consequential in the opposite direction: a rating of 9 rather than 5 out of 10 increased choice by 11.6 pp (3.3 to 19.8). Several place types were preferred to a downtown mixed-use city setting, including a small town (+15.8 pp; 7.6 to 24.0) and a rural area (+13.5 pp; 5.0 to 21.9). The remaining presidential-vote and racial-composition contrasts were smaller, and their intervals included zero. These estimates use the package's repeated-task reliability correction; the 95% intervals cluster uncertainty by respondent and therefore account for the multiple profiles evaluated by each person.

![Figure 1. Average marginal component effects on profile choice.](figures/amce-dotwhisker.png)

*Figure 1. Average marginal component effects (AMCEs) on the probability that a profile is chosen. Points are reliability-corrected estimates and whiskers are respondent-clustered 95% confidence intervals; reference levels are plotted at zero.*
